docs.abstract: Peter T. King, the longest-serving Republican in New York’s congressional delegation, will join a growing Republican exodus from the House ahead of 2020.
docs.snippet: Peter T. King, the longest-serving Republican in New York’s congressional delegation, will join a growing Republican exodus from the House ahead of 2020.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Representative Peter T. King, the longest-serving Republican in New York’s congressional delegation, said on Monday that he would retire, joining a growing exodus of Republicans from Congress ahead of the 2020 elections.

headline.main: Peter King, Veteran New York Republican in House, Announces He Will Retire
headline.print_headline: King, New York G.O.P. Stalwart in House, Announces Retirement

docs.abstract: These lawmakers are poised to take center stage in televised impeachment hearings that begin Wednesday.
docs.snippet: These lawmakers are poised to take center stage in televised impeachment hearings that begin Wednesday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When the curtain rises on the first formal day of televised impeachment hearings into President Trump, members of the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence will be seated on the dais, questioning witnesses alongside the lead Democratic and Republican investigators. The committee, affectionately known on Capitol Hill by its acronym, HPSCI (pronounced “hip-see”), is charged with overseeing the nation’s intelligence agencies, and has been leading the closed-door impeachment inquiry. The panel has 22 members — 13 Democrats and nine Republicans. Here’s a look at some of the key members.

headline.main: Here Are the Key Members to Watch on the House Intelligence Committee

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Democrats moved quickly on Monday to bring their impeachment case against President Trump into the open, saying they would forgo court battles with defiant witnesses and would vote this week on procedures to govern nationally televised hearings.

docs.abstract: The top American diplomat in Ukraine, who is to be the first witness in public House impeachment hearings, told investigators it was Rudolph W. Giuliani who instigated the Ukraine pressure campaign.
docs.snippet: The top American diplomat in Ukraine, who is to be the first witness in public House impeachment hearings, told investigators it was Rudolph W. Giuliani who instigated the Ukraine pressure campaign.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The top American diplomat in Ukraine identified Rudolph W. Giuliani, President Trump’s personal lawyer, as the instigator behind the drive to get Ukraine’s president to announce investigations into Mr. Trump’s political rivals, telling impeachment investigators last month that Mr. Giuliani was acting on behalf of the president.
